learningOnly_highVar_1.comments: I noticed that the first part of the word identified the type of shape, and the second part of the word identified the color, but I was unable to remember which was which. The hard part of the study was that the shapes and words flashed so fast that I did not have enough time to let my brain make a connection between the first part of the word and the shape and between the next part of the word and the color. I was only able to remember that anything starting with buvee was a pentagon.

I just tried to memorize every word that I read and heard, and yes the words have an unusual pattern of sounding extremely similar to each other. It was difficult to remember the different spelling for words that had the same pronunciation.
I think that most of the grey objects end with letter "h"
It was difficult and only near the end I learned the endings better.
It was hard to remember the different shapes/colours with the different endings to the words, as the differences between the spellings was quite slight.

learningOnly_highVar_2.comments: It was clear from the beginning each colour corresponded to a relatively similar structure of the final segment of the word, and that each symbol corresponded to an equal initial segment. However, the text-to-speech modulator used in this study was incredibly subpar. The TTS actively harmed learning new words, because it pronounced each colour variation almost exactly the same. I do not know if that was the intent of the study or a side effect, but I found it easier to memorize if I tried to actively ignore the voice.
this study was difficult for my, I had some strategies but sometimes I was wrong
It was a very hard task, at some point I tried not to hear the sounds to check if I could learn the words better by only reading them, but it was the same.
I was looking on colors and try to match them with different figures but it wasn't a good strategy because they weren't matched
